                <h4>
                    <b>Hadoop TestDFSIO benchmarks</b>
                </h4>

                <p>
                    Apache Hadoop is a collection of open-source software utilities that facilitate using a network of many computers to solve problems involving massive amounts of data and computation. It provides a software framework for distributed storage and processing of big data using the MapReduce programming model. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apache_Hadoop">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apache_Hadoop</a>
                </p>

                <p>
                    TestDFSIO is a benchmark tool included in Hadoop distributions which measures the peformance of a Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS) cluster to read and write data. It is intended to give an estimate of the amount of available IO bandwidth to process data.
                </p>

                <p>
                   Graph below shows TestDFSIO benchmark results when a Hadoop DataNode was deployed using Phalanx vs conventional ext4 and XFS. Note that Phalanx was paired with <a href="https://www.westerndigital.com/products/data-center-drives/ultrastar-dc-hc600-series-hdd">WD Ultrastar DC HC620</a> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shingled_magnetic_recording">Host Managed SMR</a> device). While ext4 and XFS were paired with <a href="https://www.westerndigital.com/products/data-center-drives/ultrastar-dc-hc500-series-hdd">WD Ultrastar DC HC530</a> (legacy <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perpendicular_recording">CMR</a> device).
