                <h4>
                    <b>Ceph OSD and Rados benchmarks</b>
                </h4>

                <p>
                    Ceph is a free-software storage platform, implements object storage on a single distributed computer cluster, and provides interfaces for object-, block- and file-level storage. Ceph aims primarily for completely distributed operation without a single point of failure, scalable to the exabyte level, and freely available.
                    <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ceph_(software)">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ceph_(software)</a><br>

                </p>

                <p>
                    Ceph Object Storage Daemon (OSD) bench is a benchmark tool that is included in Ceph distributions which measures the performance of a storage node to write data. It is intended to give an estimate of the amount of available write throughput in a particular storage node.
                </p>

                <p>
                    Rados bench is yet another benchmark tool included in Ceph distributions which measures the performance of a Reliable Autonomic Distributed Object Store (RADOS) cluster to store and retrieve objects. Rados bench tests writing and sequential/random reading of objects. It is designed to give an estimate on number of objects the storage cluster can store and retrieve per second.
                </p>

                <p>
                    The graph below shows OSD bench results when a Ceph storage node was deployed using Phalanx vs conventional ext4 and XFS. Note that Phalanx was paired with <a href="https://www.westerndigital.com/products/data-center-drives/ultrastar-dc-hc600-series-hdd">WD Ultrastar DC HC620</a> (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shingled_magnetic_recording">Host Managed SMR</a> device). While ext4 and XFS were paired with <a href="https://www.westerndigital.com/products/data-center-drives/ultrastar-dc-hc500-series-hdd">WD Ultrastar DC HC530</a> (legacy <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perpendicular_recording">CMR</a> device).
